---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const organSystems = [
  { slug: 'cardiovascular',      label: 'Cardiovascular' },
  { slug: 'renal',               label: 'Renal' },
  { slug: 'respiratory',         label: 'Respiratory' },
  { slug: 'gastrointestinal',    label: 'Gastrointestinal' },
  { slug: 'endocrine',           label: 'Endocrine' },
  { slug: 'reproductive',        label: 'Reproductive' },
  { slug: 'cns',                 label: 'CNS' },
  { slug: 'pns-autonomic',       label: 'PNS/Autonomic' },
  { slug: 'musculoskeletal',     label: 'Musculoskeletal' },
  { slug: 'hematology-oncology', label: 'Hematology-Oncology' },
  { slug: 'immunology',          label: 'Immunology' },
  { slug: 'infectious-disease',  label: 'Infectious Disease' },
  { slug: 'dermatology',         label: 'Dermatology' },
  { slug: 'ophthalmology-ent',   label: 'Ophthalmology/ENT' },
  { slug: 'toxicology',          label: 'Toxicology' },
];

const therapClasses = [
  { slug: 'adrenergic',             label: 'Adrenergic' },
  { slug: 'cholinergic',            label: 'Cholinergic' },
  { slug: 'ion-channel',            label: 'Ion Channel' },
  { slug: 'enzyme-inhibitors',      label: 'Enzyme Inhib.' },
  { slug: 'receptor-antagonists',   label: 'Rec. Antag.' },
  { slug: 'transporter-inhibitors', label: 'Transporter Inhib.' },
  { slug: 'hormones-analogs',       label: 'Hormones' },
  { slug: 'biologics',              label: 'Biologics' },
  { slug: 'antimicrobials',         label: 'Antimicrobials' },
  { slug: 'cytotoxics',             label: 'Cytotoxics' },
  { slug: 'anticoagulants',         label: 'Anticoagulants' },
];

// Build matrix[organ][class] = count
const matrix: Record<string, Record<string, number>> = {};
for (const org of organSystems) {
  matrix[org.slug] = {};
  for (const tc of therapClasses) {
    matrix[org.slug][tc.slug] = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d =>
      (d.organ_systems || []).includes(org.slug) &&
      (d.therapeutic_classes || []).includes(tc.slug)
    ).length;
  }
}
---

<SchemaLayout title="Organ × Class Matrix" schema="organ-by-class">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-serif font-bold mb-6">Schema 3: Organ System × Therapeutic Class Matrix</h1>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-8">
    <p>
      The organ-system-by-therapeutic-class matrix represents the most clinically integrated
      view of pharmacology available to the student, because it simultaneously encodes two
      orthogonal axes of medical knowledge: <em>where</em> a drug acts (the organ system) and
      <em>how</em> it acts (the molecular mechanism family). A β-blocker, for example, appears in
      the cardiovascular row under Adrenergic, but also in the CNS row, the renal row, and the
      respiratory row—each intersection revealing a distinct clinical application or risk
      profile. The student who understands this multidimensionality can anticipate off-target
      effects, predict drug repurposing opportunities, and reason fluently through polypharmacy
      scenarios rather than memorizing each combination in isolation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each cell in the matrix below represents the count of drugs in this reference database
      that belong to both the organ system (row) and the therapeutic class (column). Cells
      colored with a prominent badge contain five or more drugs, signaling a clinically dense
      intersection worth deep study. Grey-shaded empty cells represent mechanistic combinations
      that are currently absent from the top-500 drug list—sometimes because such combinations
      do not exist pharmacologically, and sometimes because the agents at that intersection are
      rare enough to fall outside the high-yield curriculum. Clicking any non-zero cell opens a
      dedicated intersection page listing every drug at that node, organized by subclass, with
      a brief explanation of why this mechanism is deployed in this organ system.
    </p>
    <p>
      The matrix is particularly valuable for recognizing drug repurposing patterns. Enzyme
      inhibitors dominate both the cardiovascular and the endocrine rows because ACE inhibitors,
      statins, DPP-4 inhibitors, and aromatase inhibitors all exploit the same mechanistic
      strategy—enzyme active-site blockade—applied to different biological substrates. Similarly,
      receptor antagonists span nearly every organ system, from α1-blockade in the cardiovascular
      column to dopamine-D2 antagonism in the CNS column, illustrating that receptor-level
      antagonism is the single most versatile pharmacodynamic strategy in clinical medicine.
      Use this matrix in conjunction with Schema 4 (Mechanism-First) and Schema 1
      (Organ Systems) for the most complete cross-referencing experience.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-base-300 shadow">
    <table class="table table-pin-rows table-sm w-full">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-base-200">
          <th class="font-serif text-sm sticky left-0 bg-base-200 z-10 min-w-[140px]">Organ System</th>
          {therapClasses.map(tc => (
            <th class="text-center text-xs font-medium px-2 whitespace-nowrap">{tc.label}</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {organSystems.map((org, i) => (
          <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-base-100' : 'bg-base-50'}>
            <td class="font-semibold text-sm sticky left-0 bg-inherit z-10 border-r border-base-200">
              <a href={`${base}schemas/01-organ-systems/${org.slug}/`} class="link link-hover">{org.label}</a>
            </td>
            {therapClasses.map(tc => {
              const count = matrix[org.slug][tc.slug];
              const href = `${base}schemas/03-organ-by-class/${org.slug}-${tc.slug}/`;
              return (
                <td class="text-center px-1 py-1">
                  {count === 0 ? (
                    <span class="block w-full h-6 rounded bg-base-200 opacity-40"></span>
                  ) : count >= 5 ? (
                    <a href={href} class="tooltip" data-tip={`${count} drugs`}>
                      <span class="badge badge-primary badge-sm font-bold">{count}</span>
                    </a>
                  ) : (
                    <a href={href} class="tooltip" data-tip={`${count} drug${count > 1 ? 's' : ''}`}>
                      <span class="badge badge-outline badge-sm">{count}</span>
                    </a>
                  )}
                </td>
              );
            })}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="badge badge-primary badge-sm font-bold">9</span>
      <span class="text-base-content/70">≥5 drugs (high-yield intersection)</span>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="badge badge-outline badge-sm">2</span>
      <span class="text-base-content/70">1–4 drugs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="block w-6 h-4 rounded bg-base-200 opacity-40"></span>
      <span class="text-base-content/70">No drugs at this intersection</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</SchemaLayout>
